<div id="review_6186918" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/6186918" />
    <a title="Derek" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/373022-derek"><img alt="Derek" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1189764134p2/373022.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/6186918?book_show_action=true">Sep 14, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Derek" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Derek" href="/user/show/373022-derek">Derek</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer6186918" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16720256882332683962">Flowery and ultimately meaningless<br/><br/>There are many beautifully descriptive passages, mostly of the wind &amp; snow; the best are those concerning the magical horse Althansor. Unfortunately, there are many of them, and I found my heart beginning to sink whenever another chapter began with another beautifully descriptive passage about the wind &amp; snow.<br/><br/>I never did discover a plot. The human characters came and went without any real impact, either on the story or on me, although the magical horse is charac</span>
  <span id="freeText16720256882332683962" style="display:none">Flowery and ultimately meaningless<br /><br />There are many beautifully descriptive passages, mostly of the wind &amp; snow; the best are those concerning the magical horse Althansor. Unfortunately, there are many of them, and I found my heart beginning to sink whenever another chapter began with another beautifully descriptive passage about the wind &amp; snow.<br /><br />I never did discover a plot. The human characters came and went without any real impact, either on the story or on me, although the magical horse is characterized probably better than most. Peter Lake does span the whole novel, but he spends the final part in a daze of incomprehension which I shared. The occasional moments of drama all resolved easily and without any great surprises.<br /><br />I was irritated by the wholesale dismissal of non-central characters, but it seemed I was expected to believe in the city (I am reluctant to call it New York because it is obviously not a real place) and care what happened to it.<br /><br />In the end, I felt no attachment to the city, and it seemed, finally, that the author didn't either.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16720256882332683962" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


